## Section 2: Access Reviews & Certifications

**11. Walk me through how you'd conduct a quarterly access certification for a production SQL instance.**
- Export all logins, role memberships, and explicit permissions
- Send to data/application owners for sign-off (who needs access and why)
- Flag discrepancies (orphaned, excessive, or unused accounts)
- Remediate flagged items and retain signed certification as evidence

**12. An access review reveals a manager certified access for an employee who left the company 3 months ago. How do you handle it?**
- Immediately revoke/disable the account
- Document the false certification as a control failure
- Notify Security/Audit of the exception and corrective action
- Review the certifier's other approvals for similar gaps

**13. How do you prove to an auditor that access reviews are happening on schedule?**
- Maintain a tracking log/calendar of review cycles with completion dates
- Retain signed certification documents (email/ticket approvals)
- Show remediation tickets tied to findings from each review
- Provide a sample walkthrough of one full review cycle

**14. What's your process when an access review can't be completed on time?**
- Notify Security/Compliance of the delay with a revised date
- Document the reason (resourcing, system access issues, etc.)
- Prioritize high-risk accounts (privileged/sysadmin) for interim review
- Complete the full review and close the gap with documented evidence

**15. How do you identify "toxic combinations" of permissions (e.g., a user who can both create and approve changes)?**
- Map roles to functions (create, approve, execute, audit)
- Run permission reports cross-referenced against role definitions
- Flag users holding conflicting role combinations
- Work with app/business owners to split duties or add compensating monitoring

**16. A senior executive demands permanent elevated access "because of their role." How do you respond?**
- Explain least-privilege policy applies regardless of seniority
- Offer task-specific, time-bound access when genuinely needed
- Escalate to Security/Compliance if pressure continues
- Document the request and resolution for audit trail

**17. How do you handle access certification for break-glass/emergency accounts?**
- Maintain a separate register for emergency accounts
- Require password vaulting/check-out process with logging
- Review every usage instance post-event (who, when, why)
- Certify the account list itself quarterly even if unused

**18. What evidence do you retain to show a terminated employee's access was revoked within SLA?**
- Timestamped ticket showing termination notification received
- Timestamped login disable/drop action in SQL Server logs
- Calculated time-to-revoke compared against policy SLA
- Exception report if SLA was missed, with root cause

**19. How would you respond if an auditor asks for a complete list of who can access PII/sensitive data fields?**
- Maintain a data classification map (tables/columns with PII)
- Cross-reference permissions (table/column/view level) against that map
- Include role-based and direct grants in the report
- Provide alongside encryption/masking controls applied to those fields

**20. How do you handle a situation where the "data owner" for an application no longer exists in the org chart?**
- Escalate to IT/Business leadership to assign a new owner
- Use the application's manager or department head as interim owner
- Document the gap as a finding until resolved
- Avoid leaving access uncertified — assign interim accountability

