## Section 7: Backup, Recovery & DR Audit Readiness

**61. How do you prove your backup strategy meets the company's RPO/RTO requirements?**
- Document RPO/RTO per system criticality tier
- Map backup frequency (full/diff/log) to required RPO
- Provide restore test timing results to validate RTO achievability
- Review/update the mapping annually or after major changes

**62. An auditor asks for evidence of the last successful full restore test. What do you show?**
- Restore test log/report (date, database, duration, result)
- CHECKDB output on the restored copy confirming integrity
- Ticket/calendar entry showing scheduled recurring test cadence
- Sign-off from DBA team lead on test completion

**63. How do you handle backup failures to ensure they're caught and remediated promptly?**
- Automated alerting on backup job failure (email/Teams/SIEM)
- Defined SLA for investigating and re-running failed backups
- Escalation path if backups fail repeatedly
- Weekly backup health report reviewed by DBA team

**64. How do you secure backup files to prevent unauthorized access to sensitive data?**
- Encrypt backups (backup encryption or TDE-encrypted source)
- Restrict file system/share permissions on backup destinations
- Restrict access to backup management tools/consoles
- Periodically audit who has access to backup repositories

**65. What's your DR testing process for a three-node Always On Availability Group?**
- Scheduled planned failover tests to secondary replicas
- Validate application connectivity post-failover (listener/DNS)
- Document failover time and any manual steps required
- Failback and confirm synchronization health afterward; record results

**66. How do you ensure backup retention complies with regulatory requirements (e.g., 7-year retention for financial records)?**
- Define retention policy per data/system classification
- Configure backup job retention settings and offsite/archive storage accordingly
- Periodically audit actual retained backups against policy
- Document and remediate any gaps (e.g., missing months)

**67. How would you respond if an auditor finds that DR failover hasn't been tested in over a year?**
- Acknowledge the gap and assess risk exposure
- Schedule and execute a DR test promptly, even if scoped/partial
- Document results and remediation for any issues found
- Establish a recurring DR test calendar going forward with sign-off

**68. How do you validate that a restored database doesn't introduce stale or unauthorized data into production?**
- Restores to production require change approval, just like other changes
- Validate source backup integrity and timestamp before restore
- Compare row counts/checksums on critical tables post-restore
- Document restore in change/incident records with justification

**69. How do you handle backup/restore procedures for databases containing PII when restoring to lower environments?**
- Restore to an isolated environment first
- Apply data masking/anonymization before making accessible to dev/test users
- Restrict access to the masking/restore process itself
- Document the SOP and retain evidence it was followed each time

**70. What documentation would you maintain to demonstrate your AG patching SOP doesn't compromise availability or data integrity?**
- Documented rolling, secondary-first patching sequence
- Pre/post patch validation steps (replica health, sync status)
- Rollback plan if a patched node fails to rejoin the AG
- Patch records correlated with change tickets and maintenance windows

