## C. Repeatable Audit Evidence: SOX, Internal Audits, Security Assessments, Regulatory Reviews
*(Resume: "Produced repeatable audit evidence for SOX/internal audits, security assessments, regulatory reviews")*

**14. What does "repeatable" audit evidence mean in practice, and why does it matter?**
- Evidence generated the same way, on a schedule, regardless of who's asking or when
- Reduces last-minute scrambling when an audit request comes in
- Increases consistency/comparability across audit cycles
- Built via standardized scripts/queries and templated report formats, run on a recurring basis

**15. Walk me through a standardized evidence package you'd maintain for SOX database controls.**
- Access listing (privileged users, role memberships) as of period-end
- Change management log reconciled against actual DDL/config changes
- Backup/restore test results for the period
- Access certification sign-offs for the period
- Audit log extracts for privileged activity

**16. How do you handle the fact that SOX, internal audit, and security assessments often ask for overlapping but slightly different evidence?**
- Build a "master evidence library" covering the common core (access, change, backup, audit logs)
- Tag/format each piece so it can be reused across different audit types with minimal rework
- Maintain a mapping of which evidence satisfies which framework's specific control language
- Reduces duplicate effort and inconsistency between audit responses

**17. How do you ensure evidence produced today would still make sense to someone reviewing it a year from now?**
- Include clear timestamps, scope, and methodology notes with every evidence artifact
- Use consistent naming conventions and file/folder structures
- Store alongside the script/query used to generate it (so it's reproducible)
- Avoid one-off manual edits that aren't documented

**18. A regulator asks for evidence going back 18 months that you didn't proactively generate at the time. How do you respond?**
- Check whether underlying logs/data still exist (retention permitting) to reconstruct evidence retroactively
- If reconstruction is possible, generate it but clearly label it as "retrospectively compiled on [date]"
- If data no longer exists due to retention limits, document that limitation and what is available
- Use this gap as justification to formalize ongoing evidence generation going forward

**19. How do you handle requests for evidence that would require pulling data from a system you don't directly manage (e.g., AD, ticketing tool)?**
- Identify the system owner and establish a recurring data-sharing arrangement
- Define what specific extract/report is needed and how often
- Document the end-to-end evidence chain (DB data + AD data + ticket data) so it's clear how pieces connect
- Build this into the "repeatable" evidence package as a coordinated, multi-source artifact

**20. How would you respond if an auditor says your evidence format is "not sufficient" even though it contains the right data?**
- Ask specifically what's missing from their perspective (context, sign-off, timestamps, etc.)
- Adjust the template to address the specific gap going forward
- Avoid being defensive — treat it as refining the repeatable template for future cycles
- Document the updated format as the new standard

